
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `lslocks` baraye didan ghoofl-ha (locks) dar system Linux estefade mishavad. In dastoor neshon midahad che process-haee file-ha ya resources-ha ra ghoofl karde-and.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `lslocks` --> 📜 Namayesh hameye ghoofl-haye system.
    🔹 `lslocks -n` --> 👁️‍🗨️ Namayesh id-haye adadi (numerical IDs) be jaye nam-ha.
    🔹 `lslocks -p <PID>` --> 🎯 Namayesh ghoofl-haye process ba PID moshakhas.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ lslocks

    🔹 Namayesh hameye ghoofl-haye fa'al dar system.

    $ lslocks -p 1234

    🔹 Namayesh ghoofl-haye process ba shenaseye (ID) 1234.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ lslocks | grep my_file.txt

    🔹 Peida kardan process-haee ke file `my_file.txt` ra ghoofl karde-and.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `lslocks` command is used to display information about locks held on Linux systems. It shows which processes are holding locks on files or other resources.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `lslocks` --> 📜 Show all system locks.
    🔹 `lslocks -n` --> 👁️‍🗨️ Show numerical IDs instead of names.
    🔹 `lslocks -p <PID>` --> 🎯 Show locks held by the process with the specified PID.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ lslocks

    🔹 Display all active locks on the system.

    $ lslocks -p 1234

    🔹 Display locks held by the process with ID 1234.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ lslocks | grep my_file.txt

    🔹 Find processes that are holding locks on the file `my_file.txt`.
